let _markdown = "\n\n# Getting Started with Chr3D\n\n**Your guide to understanding how chromosomes fold up inside cells**\n\n## Welcome!\n\nIf you're here, you probably have some chromatin interaction data and want to understand what it actually means. Or maybe you're just curious about how 2 meters of DNA fits into a space 100x smaller without turning into a tangled mess.\n\nEither way, you're in the right place.\n\nChr3D handles Hi-C, ChIA-PET, and HiChIP data in one place—no more juggling six different tools, three programming languages, and a pile of bash scripts held together with duct tape.\n\n***\n\n## What You'll Find Here\n\nRight now, we're building out comprehensive **Hi-C documentation** that covers:\n\n* **The biology**: What TADs, loops, compartments, and boundaries actually are\n* **The proteins**: How CTCF, cohesin, and other regulators organize chromatin in 3D\n* **The interpretation**: How to read your contact maps and understand what patterns mean\n* **The practice**: Quality control, resolution considerations, and analysis workflows\n\nThink of this as your complete guide to Hi-C—from \"what am I even looking at?\" to \"here's what my data tells me about gene regulation.\"\n\n**ChIA-PET and HiChIP documentation** are coming soon. These techniques have their own quirks and advantages, and we'll cover them in dedicated sections once the Hi-C foundation is solid.\n\n***\n\n## 🧬 Understanding Hi-C\n\nBefore diving into analysis, it helps to understand what you're actually measuring. Here's where to start:\n\n### **Start Here**\n\n* **[What is Hi-C?](getting-started/understanding-hic/intro-to-hic)** - The big picture: why we crosslink cells, cut up DNA, and sequence the pieces that were touching in 3D space\n* **[How does it work?](getting-started/understanding-hic/intro-to-hic)** - Step-by-step walkthrough of the protocol\n* **[When should I use which technique?](getting-started/understanding-hic/comparison-techniques)** - Hi-C vs ChIA-PET vs HiChIP\n\n***\n\n## 🏗️ The Structures You'll Find\n\nHi-C reveals that chromosomes aren't random tangles—they have organized structures at multiple scales.\n\n### A/B Compartments\n\nThe genome separates into \"A\" compartments (open, active genes) and \"B\" compartments (closed, silent genes). Think of it like oil and water separating in the nucleus.\n\n### TADs (Topologically Associating Domains)\n\nThese are neighborhoods where DNA interacts mostly with itself, typically 200kb-1Mb in size. Enhancers usually only talk to promoters in the same TAD.\n\n### Chromatin Loops\n\nDirect contacts between specific genomic sites, often bringing enhancers and promoters together. These are the details that matter for gene regulation.\n\n### Chromosome Territories\n\nEach chromosome lives in its own region of the nucleus. Interactions between different chromosomes are rare—which is why you see a strong diagonal in Hi-C contact maps.\n\n***\n\n## The Molecular Players\n\nStructures don't just appear magically. Here are the proteins doing the heavy lifting:\n\n### CTCF - The Boundary Guard\n\nThis protein sits at TAD boundaries like a stop sign, blocking loop extrusion. About 33,000 binding sites across the human genome. When CTCF is gone, boundaries dissolve.\n\n### Cohesin - The Loop Builder\n\nA ring-shaped complex that literally extrudes chromatin loops. It loads onto DNA, starts pushing out a loop, and keeps going until it hits CTCF or falls off. The whole process takes just a few minutes.\n\n### The Loop Extrusion Model\n\nThis is the current best explanation for how TADs and loops form. It's elegant, it's dynamic, and you can actually see it happening in live cells now.\n\n### Other Key Regulators\n\nYY1, Mediator, LDB1—there's a whole cast of characters that organize chromatin in cohesin-independent ways.\n\n***\n\n## 🎯 Why This Matters: Gene Regulation in 3D\n\nThe 3D organization of chromosomes isn't just structurally interesting—it controls which genes turn on or off.\n\n### Enhancer-Promoter Communication\n\nEnhancers can be hundreds of kilobases away from the genes they regulate. Loops bring them together in 3D space.\n\n### Boundaries Keep Things Organized\n\nTAD boundaries prevent enhancers from accidentally activating the wrong gene. When boundaries break (like in cancer), chaos ensues.\n\n### Structure Follows Function\n\nActive genes cluster together in active compartments. Silent genes do the same. The 3D architecture reflects and reinforces transcriptional states.\n\n### Everything Changes\n\nDuring mitosis, all loops dissolve. After cell division, they reform in about 20-60 minutes. During differentiation, the whole 3D landscape reorganizes to support new gene expression programs.\n\n***\n\n## 📊 Reading Your Data\n\nNow for the practical part—understanding what you're looking at.\n\n### Contact Maps 101\n\nLearn to read Hi-C heatmaps. Diagonal = nearby stuff touching (expected). Off-diagonal dots = loops (interesting). Triangles = TADs. Checkerboard = compartments.\n\n### Resolution vs Sequencing Depth\n\nHigher resolution is great, but it costs you. For human genomes: \\~100M reads gets you TADs, \\~6B reads gets you fine loops. Choose wisely based on your question and budget.\n\n### Pattern Recognition\n\nDots, stripes, triangles, plaid—each pattern tells a biological story. Learn what they mean and what they reveal about chromatin organization.\n\n### Quality Control\n\nHow to tell if your Hi-C experiment actually worked. Check these metrics before spending weeks analyzing bad data.\n\n***\n\n## 🚀 Ready to Analyze Your Data?\n\nHere's where to go next depending on what you need:\n\n**New to Hi-C?** Start with What is Hi-C?[](understanding-hic/intro-to-hic) and work through the biological structures. Understanding what you're measuring makes analysis much easier.\n\n**Have data, need results?** Jump to our tutorials for complete workflows from FASTQ files to publication-ready figures. *(Coming soon)*\n\n**Want to customize things?** Check out the API Reference to build your own analysis pipelines. *(Coming soon)*\n\n**Command-line person?** The CLI Reference has everything you need for script-based workflows. *(Coming soon)*\n\n***\n\n## What Makes Chr3D Different?\n\nMost Hi-C tools are either powerful but impossible to install, or easy to use but limited. We're trying to hit the sweet spot: everything in Python, unified installation, flexible API, and workflows that actually match how researchers think about their experiments.\n\nThink of it as the \"scanpy for 3D genomics\"—a complete ecosystem where you can go from raw data to biological insights without switching between six different tools.\n\nLet's figure out what your chromosomes are doing.\n";
